issue_body:
(This is copied from #220 for follow up)

Initial Issue: Somehow the Devices has only RTL-TCP enabled, and all other devices options are greyed out. I enabled it uder ~/.config/urh.ini, but starting reset everything back to disabled. I'm sure that my RTL-SDR is correctly installed, as gqrx is running fine. But do I need gnuradion to be able to use it under URH, as I was unable to install the full gnuradio yet?

@jopohl : For devices you should ensure that you have the required libs installed on your system. What does locate rtlsdr.so say? You should not enable devices manually in ini. Native backend should work for you if you installed rtlsdr.so, you can use the rebuild button in device options for this.

@cirla 
This good library cannot be installed on Windows without installing "Microsoft Visual C++ Build Tools".
I think it would be better to add some comments about this issue. (Under "Installation")

The following code is legal `C++`:

```c++
class Stop;
class Go;

//! stores a handler for each message type.
template<typename T>
struct messageHandlers {
    typedef std::function<void (const T&)> type;
    static type handler;
};

template <typename T> typename messageHandlers<T>::type messageHandlers<T>::handler;
template messageHandlers<Go>::type messageHandlers<Go>::handler;
template messageHandlers<Stop>::type messageHandlers<Stop>::handler;
```

Note that there are deliberately no `<>` after the word `template`, as this would declare a specialization of some kind. Instead `template` is required here to tell the compiler to parse 

This gives an incorrect warning in breathe:
```
<path>\doc\hardware.rst:25: WARNING: Invalid definition: Expected '<' after 'template' [error at 9]
  template messageHandlers< GetLogs >::type messageHandlers::handler
  ---------^
```

As it turns out, there's a way of expressing this without this syntax, so this isn't an issue for me - but it is still a bug in breath

The default misfire_grace_time value for a job is set 1 in Job.__init__():

    #!python
    class Job(object):
        def __init__(self, trigger, func, args, kwargs, name=None,
                     misfire_grace_time=1, max_runs=None, max_concurrency=1):



So the following code in Schedule.add_job() does not work: 

    #!python

    class Scheduler(object):
        def add_job():
            ...
            job = Job(trigger, func, args or [], kwargs or {}, **options)
            if job.misfire_grace_time is None:
                job.misfire_grace_time = self.misfire_grace_time
            ...




