```
Of course, `N` is also known to python and `Interval` has a bunch of other methods.

Now the following happens:
```python
> i = Interval(1,2)
> print(i)
[1,2]
> i.lower()
[1,2]
> i.upper()
2
```
`lower()` seems to return the object itself, not the member it is supposed to. `upper()` however works fine, though everything is implemented analogously.

We have unit tests in place for the C++ side, `Interval::lower()` works fine.

I managed to find a workaround here: using `.def("lower", &Interval::lower, py::return_value_policy::reference_internal)` actually fixes the problem.
